description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1dB5SaZQutf

This is a MakerBot PRINT not a real ice cream cone!  
Ice cream can heal the world.  We all love ice cream, so too, can we all be friends.  Print it, have it, taste it.

This delectable cone was printed with a Thing-O-Matic with MK7 at .27mm layer height and 30% infill. I scanned an ice cream cone piggie bank with 123D Catch to generate the model for this print.
Print the first file icecreamcone10 without a raft or support.  It will break free easily from the base it prints on.  Icecreamcone10 is the entire cone, you can either print it all out in one print with one color.  Or you can swap filaments while printing the ice cream part for a great effect.  
You can also, stop the print once the cone is done printing, and then print the ice cream top separately, and glue the two together.  The ice cream top must be printed with support and a raft.  
For the cone in the photo I took the last approach and I glued the two pieces together.

comments.text: Wish the cone by itself was posted since the ice cream top was. Kind of crazy to have to monitor the print job and figure out when to stop it if you just want the cone. I printed two tops: one black and one white before I saw that there is no cone file.

author: KevinPrints

description.text:
This is an experiment.
I used two designs and combined them into one, and then split them and a lot of stuff.
The idea is to have a scope mount for picatinny rail mounts. The inside diameter of the mount is 28-29mm (depending on shrinkage of ABS), I have not printed one yet.
the reason it is split, like it is, is cause i originally had it as one single piece, but then realised that various scopes may vary in size of the gap, and length, etc. So i hope this allows for some form of free movement when mounting.
You will need 6 x 3m or 4m nuts and bolts - two 20mm and four 10mm lengths.
All credit for the original designs go to the guys that made them (sorry i cant remember who they were or where i got them, the were on my PC, and I did not keep the original details).

I added a single section to the thingy files, print one of them twice, or download the file with both together. Hope that saves some plastic somewhere for someone :)

description.text: Got board and decided I wanted to design a space ship on tinkercad.com; this is what I came up with. The fighter has bubble canopies for crew, 2 front cannons, a movable laser turret, and 4 engines. It is ready for a name and to join the fleet for battle!

Notes:

The fighter itself does not need a raft. The laser turret does need a raft. I needed supports for both of them; although -- some printers may not.

Putting in the laser turret

This was difficult! First: I had to twist and push the turret in until it was stuck a little bit and close to straight. Second: I used a pliers (any sturdy metal or strong material will do), placed the fighter on a table, and pushed the turret in using the flat side of the pliers. title: IEC320/C14 Plug Mount for 40mm vslot Extrusion

description.text:
This is a mount for an iec320/c14 socket and switch I found on amazon: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00X74BUW8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

This mounts to 4040 or 2040 v slot extrusion from openbuilds.

1)Cut out the .25mm support layer above the nut traps, and insert the nuts into the traps.

2) Tamp the bottom surface onto a flat surface to seat the nut traps flush.

3) run your wiring through the bottom hole and solder it to the tabs on the back of the connector

4) bend the wiring downward in the direction of the hole, and then insert the iec320 plug into the mount

5) secure it with m3x45mm screws and washers. The bottom of the screw should be flush with or above the bottom surface of the part

6) use 4 m5x10mm screws and post assembly t-nuts to attach it all to your extrusion.

NOTE: The bottom m3 screw does run through the cable out hole. This didnt matter much to me, and gave me a place to zip tie the wires to for added support. However, you can use a shorter screw and just put the nut and a washer at the top surface of the hole if you want to free up more space for thicker wires to exit.

Changelog

title: Da VInci 1.0 Pro Filament Spool Holder

description.text:
This is a remake of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1234196/ by ChatToBrain.
The original model interfered with the opening of the lid on the Da Vinci Printer, and I preferred to not have to "pop" the lid up to allow it to be opened. I also did not want to runt he risk of someone not understanding how to use it properly and damaging the lid.

Modifications:
I used the existing U shaped hole on the back of the printer enclosure as the sole mounting point for the holder and reworked the top of the original holder. The filament hole is angled up to reduce the bends in the filament as it enters the printer.

The holder is 1 mm narrower since the u shaped hole was only 19mm wide.

Strength, Although the original design has a very strong mounting design, I have stress tested this redesign and it holds 10 lbs (4.5 kg) easily, although I would not recommend placing that much weight on the printers enclosure.

This design does not interfere with the normal XYZprinting cartidges either.

I would recommend that you use an insert in the filament guide hole to reduce filament friction as much as possible. I used a small piece of coated backing paper from a sheet of masking tape. The "peel" part of a peel and stick armband, tape, wall hanger etc would be almost the same thing.

comments.text: Also might want to watch out for electric static discharge from the vacuum, The danger is from the rapid movement of air (ions) across very static-sensitive components, with no discharge path other than the board or components. Many of them can be destroyed with as little as 30 volts of static charge, and a static discharge isn't felt until about 1500-2000 volts. Also, ESD damage doesn't necessarily show up right away. A circuit can be weakened and not fail until long after the damage is done. I have personally seen component-damage (under a microscope) immediately after using a vacuum (in an ESD-training class).
comments.author: Kastley

comments.text:
Static-sensitive components ?!
Airflow is going from the bottom of the laptop, over fans rotor to the cooler then out to vacuum cleaner. Laptop internal structure is not designed that way that airflow comes even close to some sensitive components.
Most of the laptops are designed with (http://i.stack.imgur.com/ZFbig.jpg) completely separated airflow mechanism from the rest of the electronics. One of the reasons why is that case is to isolate mechanical components (fan) from electrical.

Depending on the weather and humidity I have found that parts sometimes adhere to my plastic (Lexan) print bed and sometimes they will come loose in the middle of printing. I sand my print bed to allow maximum adhesion (printing PLA) but I still find times when the part comes off the bed while printing.

I created this simple part which I can add to anything I wish to print via my slicer software. I simply place the 'Print Pad' under the part I want to print. After the print pad is printed and when I confirm I am printing the actual part, I then put painters tape on the 'Print Pad' to hold it in place until the part is finished printing. It is thin enough that it will simply break off the part I print and with minimal sanding (Most times I don't even need to sand or trim) one really can't see that it was ever there.

description.text:
This OpenSCAD script prints a A 2-part, hinged, bolt-on holder/fixture for affixing a small packaged sensing device (in this case a custom WIMU) to a round shaft or bar allowing it to be easily attached to golf clubs, tennis racquets, pipes, cylindrical bar stock, walking sticks etc. Version:
2.3.2 Date:
2012-03-02 To Do:
Nothing Note:
you will need the mouse_ears_test.scad file in the same folder asthis file for the mouse ears to compile properly
you will need the pivot_1_0.scad file in the same folder as this file for the hinge and bolt hole to compile properly
you will need the rounded_cuboid_2_5.scad file in the same folder as this file for the object to compile properly Changes from previous versions:
v2.3.4
  • change shaft diameter to 30mm
    • v2.3.4
  • fix small elevation error for cap
  • added some tolerance to make inserting insert possible!
    • v2.3.3
  • added nubs to help locate cap onto top
  • added extra insert piece to allow device to be inserted from bottom
    v2.3.2
  • added cap
    v2.3.1
  • reduced tolerances for better fit (from 0.45 to 0.35)
    v2.3
  • removed deprecated variables
  • new variable "arm_length" determines how much extra space there is for the hinge and bolt hole
    • new variable "cutout_support_thickness" allows you to specify width of walls left in areas where support are needed such as under the arch for the shaft and the cutouts on the side of the holder
      v2.2
  • Switched to newer rounded cuboid module (v2.5) which makes positioning easier!
  • add cutouts for connections to held object
    v2.1
  • added pivot_1_0.scad module for hinge
  • Can now generate bottom half
  • Added control variables to control whether top, bottom or both are generated and whether or not they are stacked or have mouse ears
  • Added captive nut on top half
  • More parametric!
  • Rotated held object 90 degrees so I can make holes for uUSB port which would have been blocked by bolt and hinge otherwise
    v2.0
  • Completely remade parametric version in openscad based on alex's strap holder
    v1.1
  • changed some sizes to make it easier to use without rework
    v1.0
  • Original non-parametric autocad version

• Measure diameter of device to be held and cylindrical bar onto which devices will attach and modify source files accordingly. Currently the files are sized for a 10mm shaft holding a 32.7*38.66mm packaged item (one of our WIMUs)
  • Adjust the variables in the openscad code and choose options such as mouse_ears etc.
  • Print out top and bottom half of object and clean up any rough edges.
  • Drill out hinge pivot hole on bottom part to JUST less than 3mm and top part to a bit more than 3mm.
  • Assemble the top onto the bottom part of the hinge and insert a piece of 3mm printing filament so that it passes through both top and bottom, fix in place with glue or acetone on the bottom part only Note: the top and bottom part should pivot reasonably smoothly.
  • Insert Nut into recess on top part and thread matching bolt of appropriate length upwards through corresponding hole in bottom part and place onto shaft item before mating and bolt the parts together. Note: it may be a good idea to coat the rounded recesses that correspond to the shaft with rubberised paint or foam etc. to ensure a secure fit.
  • Insert sensing device into provided void.
  • Record data with device attached to rod like item.

description.text:
Several friends commented that my squid reminded them of a spider, so I decided to make a large posable spider using the joints from Ellindsey's Ball-Joint Articulated Octopus. Since I changed so many things, I have included them all here so you won't have to look elsewhere for parts. I used the Pull Chain Fobs Tarantula from 123D as a source model for the body.

Updated on 9/11/16 with all non-manifold shapes fixed.

Printer:

Delta Mini Rostock

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

I added tabs where needed, so you can print without supports. You may get some sagging due to bridging under the body, but it was minor.

I just updated the models so they are all manifold. It wasn't a problem with Cura, but might be an issue with other slicers.

Detailed Instructions for assembly

This is a pretty involved project that took about 5 hours to print in total.

You will need to print

1x Spider_Body.stl
1x Spider_Long_Leg_Segx8.stl
1x Spider_Short_Leg_Segx8.stl
1x Spider_Leg_TipX8.stl
1x Spider_Pedipalps.stl
2x Spider_joint_x8.stl

The files are also included as individual parts if you want to arrange them yourself.

After printing you will need to remove the tabs and trim up the ball end of the joints. There are many parts, so this will take a while.

To assemble, I put the legs together first. You need to start at the body in this order: joint, short segment, joint, long segment, leg tip. You will need to build 8 leg assemblies.

For the pedipalps: joint,segment,tip. The pedipalps are 25% smaller to look correct. You will need to build 2 pedipalp assemblies.

Snap the legs into the body sockets and the pedipalps into the two smaller front sockets and you are done.

As an experiment, I tried to tighten the joints and make them a little more "natural" by adding a small amount of hot-melt glue to the inside of the joint. This worked well, but was messy and you had to be sure not to put too much in. It does allow the joints to support themselves though. I wonder if silicone seal might have worked better. I may try that on the squid or the next spider I print.

The print is quite large. You can try to scale it, but the joints may not scale properly.

Designed in TInkerCad

I did all of the work in TinkerCad. The original model was not articulated, so I had to use "Holes" to remove the legs and pedipalps. I then added sockets to the body and filled in the gaps using some of the TinkerCad Shape Generators. I extended the joint segments by combining two joints with a cylinder between them. The pedipalps were the same parts, just reduced by 25%. I also rounded the original tips a little so they weren't so sharp.

After designing more variations than I wish to remember, of a fan holder to fit my UM, I discovered that the original UM holder supplied with the kit worked better in many situations. Although it does not deliver a blast of air just to the tip of the nozzle, it does give a massive flow rate spread over a very useful footprint. Thus it cools the already printed plastic which is often missed by more finely aimed blasts of air when the head is moving at speed. My goal was to design a copy of the supplied UM fan mount that is printable in one piece - without the use of support material. Designed for when you have crashed and broken the original by running it into the latest Yoda test print! Or alternatively use it to print a spare and show the rest of us up with your forethought. There are two versions
The 'Printable UM fan holder' is designed to be bolted in place using the original hardware. Then we have 'The Florian push fit variant' a special request version that just pushes into place. ( Florian, Thanks for the neat idea and subsequent testing.) Both print well with either the High or Ultra profile supplied in the Ultimaker version of Netfabb. Note: They print without a cooling fan (if you've already broken the original) but obviously they will look better printed whilst you still have a fan available. So if need be, print the fan holder twice ie the emergency rough version and then the neat permanent replacement

• 'Add part' the version of the fan holder you wish to use onto the virtual print bed in Netfabb, making sure that it loads the same way up as in the green model picture shown on this page.

  • Select either the High or Ultra profile along with the matching 'FILLED OBJECT' quality setting.

  • Print it, then clean the bolt holes if needed (not too much cleaning of the front bolt holes if its the Florian special).

  • Fix it in place and get back to printing.

Here is my extended version of r3z0's Tevo Tarantula case mk1. I wanted to be able to fit more components into the case. So I created an extended version that can fit my PSU as well as OcotoPi and 4 Channel Relay.

The side panels and base are split into 2 parts each so I could print them on a smaller bed. The shim that is included is used to superglue the two pieces together. The side panels also have screw offsets that accept m3x12mm screws or larger.

Update #5: (1/18/2017)

Fixed issue with RepRap Discount Controller not fitting the front top panel. The following files have been updated:

  1. front_top_w_sd.stl
  2. left_panel_2_w_sd.stl

Update #4:

Added a larger version to fit larger power supplies. All files are prefixed with "xl_" for this version.

Update #3:

Adjusted side panels so there isn't a small gap when assembled.

Update #2:

Side panels no longer have shims for support. Screwing the two panels together is enough support to not need shims. I've also added a separate components part that is attached to the left side panel. I mainly did this so that the components part can easily be customized and doesn't require an entire reprint of the side panel.

Front
  1. Front Top: (2 options)
    • Full Graphic Smart Controller: front_top_full.stl
    • Discount Smart Controller: front_top.stl

  2. Front Bottom: front_bottom.stl
    • Requires: 80mm Fan
Left Side
  1. Left Panel (1 of 2): left_panel_1.stl
  2. Left Panel (2 of 2): left_panel_2.stl
  3. Left Panel w/ SD (2 of 2): left_panel_2_w_sd.stl Use in conjunction with Front Top w/ SD (front_top_w_sd.stl)

description.text:
Silencio, un libro para leer con los sentidos

Silencio es una recopilación de poesias a modo de microrelatos que relatan sentimientos y experiencias sensoriales, en muchas ocasiones sinestesicas. Se trata de frases independientes, pero que también en su conjunto relatan una breve historia.

Se trata de un libro de poesia ilustrada aprovechando el relieve de la impresión 3D, para poder leer y tocar tanto para las personas videntes e invidentes, ofreciendo una comunicación táctil para todos
El libro cuenta con portada, contraportada y hoja de créditos, portada interior, 14 páginas cada una con poesía representada en los dos alfabetos, 14 páginas de ilustraciones y descripción en Braille justo debajo de estas para facilitar su comprensión.

Puedes encontrar más información en :)

http://www.tactilebook.com/

Printer:

Witbox 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

La altura de capa utilizada ha sido de 0.2 para que las paginas no tengan un grosor demasiado alto y el tiempo de impresión se reduzca. La temperatura de impresión utilizada ha sido de 235 grados para que obscile entre los 230-240 (ya que no es estable) con el fin de crear una superficie homogenea. Las retracciones deben ser lo más rápidas y distantes posibles para no que no genere residuos indeseados.

http://www.tactilebook.com/imprime-tu-libro.html

Binding

Cada página cuenta con un puente, permite la doblez de las paginas aportando mayor flexibilidad y 5 agujeros para su encuadernación.

La encuadernación fue pensada para facilitar el DIY (do it yourself). Esta encuadernación a base de encuadernadores es accesible en cualquier parte del mundo y además de económica. Además el diseño de la página abre las puertas a otras posibles encuadernaciones.

http://www.tactilebook.com/sobre-el-libro.html

The material

El material con el que está impreso el libro es filamento flexible, un material muy elastico y confortable al tacto. Además es inarrugable y se puede mojar.

Las dimensiones de la página son definidas en relación al tamaño del área de impresión medio de las actuales impresoras 3D

Para la realización de este proyecto, he tenido la suerte de poder contar con la ayuda de la organización de la ONCE, donde me han aconsejado sobre el braille, he podido resolver dudas, testear el libro y validar satisfactoriamente que cumple los requisitos para poder ser leido por personas invidentes.

http://www.tactilebook.com/como-se-hizo.html

Especial agradecimientos a La ONCE, Néstor y Paula

title: Switch Mount for Prusa I3X Geeetech carraige

description.text:
I found this 30mm Prox sensor at our local surplus store and thought I'd try it. Retail these run for about $100 but I found it for $15.00! The Prox is an Omron E2K-X15ME1 and after testing it I found that it will read my glass with PEI (Polyetherimide) attached to the top. Runs 12 to 24DCV. Also the sensor will read up to 15mm away from the bed.
I designed the mount with the lower nut inside the housing but not necessary. I just thought I would try it. Clean out of the supports was not to bad but take your time. It will mount to the lower screw holes that hold the angle supports for the extruder bed. You can leave them in place just use longer screws. 40-45mm length 3mm screws.
I used PETG for material and it worked very well at 0.2 layer height 2 perimeters and 3 top and bottom layers. All this in (Repitier) 20% infill and supports. Thanks for looking/\ Oh, feel free to go to Tinkercad to veiw the build.

A DIY midi USB host. Will convert your USB midi keyboard to DIN. No need for a computer in-between the keyboard and the synth.

Parts (cost ~25£).
USB Host card - http://www.hobbytronics.co.uk/usb-host-midi
Midi Breakout Board - http://www.hobbytronics.co.uk/midi-breakout
Voltage regulator - Used LM7805
Caps - 0.33uf , 0.1uf
LED + resistor - http://led.linear1.org/1led.wiz
On/Off switch - Used one from my junk box
9v Battery + Connector
M3 screws x4 - Bottom to top part,
Small self tapping screws x9 - Found some in my junk box, guess you can use anything that fits.

The size of the switch I used might be hard to find so I included a bottom part without any switch cutout. Then you can either drill a hole your self of make a remix that will fit your needs.
